'''Arancha González''' '''Laya '''(born 22 May 1969) is a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] economist and currently the [[Executive Director]] of the [[International Trade Centre]], the joint agency of the [[United Nations Conference on Trade and Development]] and the [[World Trade Organization]]. She was appointed to this position in August 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.intracen.org/news/UN-Secretary-General-appoints-Arancha-Gonz%C3%A1lez-of-Spain-as-Executive-Director-of-ITC/ |title=UN Secretary-General appoints Arancha González of Spain as Executive Director of ITC |author= ITC Communications |date=15 August 2013 |publisher=International Trade Centre |access-date=25 September 2015}}</ref>

==Career==
González began her career in the private sector as an associate at German law firm [[Freshfields Bruckhaus Deringer|Bruckhaus Westrick Stegemann]] advising companies on trade, competition and state aid matters. 

Between 2002 and 2005 González was the European Commission Spokeswoman for Trade and adviser to the European Commissioner [[Pascal Lamy]]. She subsequently served in various capacities in the [[European Commission]] in the area of international trade, including negotiations of trade agreements between the EU and [[Mercosur]], [[Iran]], the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]], the [[Balkans]] and Mediterranean countries. She has also assisted developing countries in benefiting from trading opportunities in Europe. 

González served as Chief of Staff [[Pascal Lamy]] in his role as WTO Director General between 2005 and 2013. In that capacity she was intimately involved in setting up the WTO's [[Aid for Trade]] initiative<ref>Ryan Heath and Eline Schaart (2018), [https://www.politico.eu/list/women-who-shape-brussels-2018-ranking/arancha-gonzalez/ Women Who Shape Brussels - 2018 Ranking: Arancha González] ''[[Politico Europe]]''.</ref> as well as the [[Enhanced integrated framework|Enhanced Integrated Framework]], a joint venture of several international organisations helping to build trade capacity in the world's poorest countries. She served as WTO Director-General's representative (Sherpa) at the [[G-20 major economies|G-20]].

==Other activities==
* [[International Gender Champions]] (IGC), Member of the Global Advisory Board<ref>[https://genderchampions.com/champions Members] [[International Gender Champions]] (IGC).</ref>
* [[Mo Ibrahim Foundation]], Member of the Advisory Council<ref>[http://mo.ibrahim.foundation/iiag/advisory-council/ Advisory Council] [[Mo Ibrahim Foundation]].</ref>
* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Co-Chair of the Global Future Council on the Future of International Trade and Investment<ref>[https://www.weforum.org/agenda/authors/arancha-gonzalez/ Arancha González Laya] [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF).</ref>

==Political positions==
González has been an outspoken advocate for Spanish unity and dialogue on the Catalan independence issue.<ref>Ryan Heath and Eline Schaart (2018), [https://www.politico.eu/list/women-who-shape-brussels-2018-ranking/arancha-gonzalez/ Women Who Shape Brussels - 2018 Ranking: Arancha González] ''[[Politico Europe]]''.</ref>

==Personal life==
Arancha González teaches on trade and development at the [[College of Europe]] (Bruges), the [[IELPO]] (Barcelona), the [[World Trade Institute]] (WTI) and the [[Shanghai Institute of Foreign Trade]].

