{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{BLP sources|date=December 2011}} {{Infobox cyclist | name = Ludo Dierckxsens | image = Ludo-dierckxsens-1359069565.jpg | fullname = Ludo Dierckxsens | nickname = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|10|14}} | birth_place = [[Geel]], [[Belgium]] | height = | weight = | currentteam = Retired | discipline = Road | role = Rider | ridertype = | amateuryears1 = | amateurteam1 = | proyears1 = 1994 | proteam1 = [[Saxon (cycling team)|Saxon]] | proyears2 = 1995 | proteam2 = [[Collstrop]] | proyears3 = 1996–1997 | proteam3 = [[Tonissteiner]] | proyears4 = 1998 | proteam4 = [[Lotto-Mobistar]] | proyears5 = 1999–2002 | proteam5 = [[Lampre-Daikin]] | proyears6 = 2003–2004 | proteam6 = [[Landbouwkrediet-Colnago]] | majorwins = 1 stage 1999 Tour de France | updated = 21 August 2013 }} '''Ludo Dierckxsens''' (born 14 October 1964 in [[Geel]], [[Flanders]]) is a former [[Belgian]] [[racing cyclist]]. He is best known for winning the 11th stage of the [[1999 Tour de France]], while competing for {{ct|LAM|1999}}.
==1999 Tour de France== Ludo Dierckxsens won the 11th stage of the 1999 Tour de France. After this stage victory, Dierckxens went to take the obligatory doping tests. When the doctors asked him the routine question if he had taken any products which might cause a positive test result, Dierckxens replied that he had taken [[tetracosactide]] (Synacthen) in the [[Tour of Germany]]. He claimed to have a prescription for them, but his team {{ct|LAM|1999}} did not know about this, and sent him home a few days later. The doping tests returned negative.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19990720&id=LC-19990720-9012&words=+jean-marie%20+leblanc%20jean%20marie%20leblanc|title=Loslippige Ludo Diercksens naar huis|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|date=20 July 1999|accessdate=7 August 2009|language=Dutch}}</ref>
